# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: blockade
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:blockade/admiral] The word *admiral* in Middle English comes from Anglo-French *amiral*, "commander", from Medieval Latin *admiralis*, *admirallus*.
[src:blockade/admiral] The 1818 edition of Samuel Johnson's *A Dictionary of the English Language*, edited and revised by the Rev.
[src:blockade/admiral] The quote from John Minsheu's Dictionarie in Spanish and English (1599), given in Johnson's Dictionary, has been confirmed as being accurate.
[src:blockade/admiral] Those Phanariots who attained the princely position of dragoman of the fleet served under the Ottoman admiral having administration of the Aegean islands and the Anatolian coast.
[src:blockade/admiral] Central Command, introduced Vice Admiral Mark I.
[src:blockade/admiral] One alternate etymology proposes that the term admiral evolved, instead, from the title of Amīr al-Umarāʾ (أمير الأمراء).
[src:blockade/admiral] Under the reign of the Buyid dynasty (934 to 1062) of Iraq and Iran, the title of Amīr al-Umarāʾ, which means prince of princes, came to denote the heir-apparent, or crown prince.
[src:blockade/admiral] This alternate etymology states that the term was in use for the Greco-Arab naval leaders (e.g.
[src:blockade/admiral] Christodulus) in the Norman-Arab-Byzantine culture of Norman Sicily, which had formerly been ruled by Arabs, at least by the early 11th century.
[src:blockade/admiral] During this time, the Norman Roger II of Sicily (1095–1154) employed a Greek Christian, known as George of Antioch, who previously had served as a naval commander for several North African Muslim rulers.
[src:blockade/admiral] Roger styled George in Abbasid fashion as *Amir of Amirs*, or Amīr al-Umarāʾ, with the title becoming Latinized in the 13th century as *ammiratus ammiratorum*.
[src:blockade/admiral] The Sicilians and later the Genoese took the first two parts of the term from their Aragon opponents and used them as one word, *amiral*. .
[src:blockade/admiral] The French gave their sea commanders similar titles while in Portuguese and Spanish the word changed to *almirante*.
[src:blockade/admiral] As the word was used by people speaking Latin or Latin-based languages it gained the "d" and endured a series of different endings and spellings leading to the English spelling *admyrall* in the 14th century and to *admiral* by the 16th century.
[src:blockade/admiral] The etymology of a word does not suggest the antiquity of the word as it may have appeared in other languages with entirely different pronunciations.
[src:blockade/admiral] The Greek ναύαρχος, for instance, which is pronounced "naúarkhos", existed from very ancient times in Greece.
[src:blockade/admiral] The word "admiral" has come to be almost exclusively associated with the highest naval rank in most of the world's navies, equivalent to the army rank of general.
[src:blockade/admiral] However, this was not always the case; for example, in some European countries prior to the end of World War II, admiral was the third highest naval rank after general admiral and grand admiral.
[src:blockade/admiral] The rank of admiral has also been subdivided into various grades, several of which are historically extinct while others remain in use in most present-day navies.
[src:blockade/admiral] The Royal Navy used the colours red, white, and blue, in descending order to indicate seniority of its admirals until 1864; for example, Horatio Nelson's highest rank was vice-admiral of the white.
[src:blockade/admiral] The generic term for these naval equivalents of army generals is flag officer.
[src:blockade/admiral] Some navies have also used army-type titles for them, such as the Cromwellian "general at sea".
[src:blockade/admiral] While the rank is used in most of NATO countries, it is ranked differently depending on the country.
[src:blockade/aerial-warfare] Modern aerial warfare includes missiles and unmanned aerial vehicles.
[src:blockade/aerial-warfare] Surface forces are likely to respond to enemy air activity with anti-aircraft warfare.
[src:blockade/aerial-warfare] The history of aerial warfare began in ancient times, with the use of man-carrying kites in Ancient China.
[src:blockade/aerial-warfare] In the third century it progressed to balloon warfare.
[src:blockade/aerial-warfare] Airships (notably zeppelins) served in military use in the early years of the 20th century.
[src:blockade/aerial-warfare] Heavier-than-air airplanes first went to war in the Italo-Turkish War in 1911, initially for aerial reconnaissance, and then for aerial combat to shoot down enemy reconnaissance planes.
[src:blockade/aerial-warfare] Aircraft continued to carry out these roles during World War I (1914-1918), where the use of planes and zeppelins for strategic bombing also emerged.
[src:blockade/aerial-warfare] The rise of fighter aircraft and of air-to-air combat led to a realisation of the desirability of achieving air superiority.
[src:blockade/aerial-warfare] Closer integration of attacking aircraft with ground operations ("battlefield support") also developed during World War I.
[src:blockade/aerial-warfare] During World War II (1939-1945), the use of strategic bombing increased, while airborne forces, missiles, and early precision-guided munitions were introduced.
[src:blockade/aerial-warfare] Aircraft carriers gained particular importance in the trans-oceanic projection of air power.
[src:blockade/aerial-warfare] Ballistic missiles became of key importance during the Cold War, were armed with nuclear warheads, and were stockpiled by the United States and the Soviet Union to deter each other from using them.
[src:blockade/aerial-warfare] Drone warfare using relatively cheap unmanned equipment proliferated in the 21st century, particularly after the start of the Second Nagorno-Karabakh War in 2020.
[src:blockade/aerial-warfare] Aerial reconnaissance is reconnaissance for a military or strategic purpose that is conducted using reconnaissance aircraft.
[src:blockade/aerial-warfare] This role can fulfil a variety of requirements, including the collection of imagery intelligence, observation of enemy maneuvers and artillery spotting.
[src:blockade/aerial-warfare] Air combat manoeuvring (also known as ACM or dogfighting) is the tactical art of moving, turning and situating a fighter aircraft in order to attain a position from which an attack can be made on another aircraft.
[src:blockade/aerial-warfare] It relies on offensive and defensive basic fighter manoeuvring (BFM) to gain an advantage over an aerial opponent.
[src:blockade/aerial-warfare] Airborne forces are military units, usually light infantry, set up to be moved by aircraft and "dropped" into battle, typically by parachute.
[src:blockade/aerial-warfare] Thus, they can be placed behind enemy lines, and have the capability to deploy almost anywhere with little warning.
[src:blockade/aerial-warfare] The formations are limited only by the number and size of their aircraft, so given enough capacity a huge force can appear "out of nowhere" in minutes, an action referred to as *vertical envelopment*.
[src:blockade/aerial-warfare] Conversely, airborne forces typically lack the supplies and equipment for prolonged combat operations, and are therefore more suited for airhead operations than for long-term occupation; furthermore, parachute operations are particularly sensitive to adverse weather conditions.
[src:blockade/aerial-warfare] Advances in helicopter technology since World War II have brought increased flexibility to the scope of airborne operations, and air assaults have largely replaced large-scale parachute operations, and (almost) completely replaced combat glider operations.
[src:blockade/aerial-warfare] An airstrike or *air strike* is an offensive operation carried out by attack aircraft.
[src:blockade/aerial-warfare] Air strikes are mostly delivered from aircraft such as fighters, bombers, ground attack aircraft, and attack helicopters.
[src:blockade/aerial-warfare] The official definition includes all sorts of targets, including enemy air targets, but in popular use the term is usually narrowed to a tactical (small-scale) attack on a ground or naval objective.
[src:blockade/aerial-warfare] Weapons used in an airstrike can range from machine gun bullets and missiles to various types of bombs.
[src:blockade/aerial-warfare] It is also commonly referred to as an *air raid*.
[src:blockade/aerial-warfare] In close air support, air strikes are usually controlled by trained observers for coordination with friendly ground troops in a manner derived from artillery tactics.
[src:blockade/aerial-warfare] Strategic bombing is a military strategy used in a total war with the goal of defeating the enemy by destroying their morale or their economic ability to produce and transport materiel to the theatres of military operations, or both.
[src:blockade/aerial-warfare] It is a systematically organized and executed attack from the air which can utilize strategic bombers, long- or medium-range missiles, or nuclear-armed fighter-bomber aircraft to attack targets deemed vital to the enemy's war-making capability.
[src:blockade/aerial-warfare] It may be used to protect naval, ground, and air forces in any location.
[src:blockade/aerial-warfare] However, for most countries the main effort has tended to be 'homeland defence'.
[src:blockade/aerial-warfare] NATO refers to airborne air defence as *counter-air* and naval air defence as *anti-aircraft warfare*.
[src:blockade/aerial-warfare] Missile defence is an extension of air defence as are initiatives to adapt air defence to the task of intercepting any projectile in flight.
[src:blockade/aerial-warfare] In modern usage, a missile is a self-propelled precision-guided munition system, as opposed to an unguided self-propelled munition, referred to as a rocket (although these too can also be guided).
[src:blockade/aerial-warfare] Missiles have four system components: targeting and/or missile guidance, flight system, engine, and warhead.
[src:blockade/aerial-warfare] Missiles come in types adapted for different purposes: surface-to-surface and air-to-surface missiles (ballistic, cruise, anti-ship, anti-tank, etc.), surface-to-air missiles (and anti-ballistic), air-to-air missiles, and anti-satellite weapons.
[src:blockade/aerial-warfare] All known existing missiles are designed to be propelled during powered flight by chemical reactions inside a rocket engine, jet engine, or other type of engine.
[src:blockade/aerial-warfare] Non-self-propelled airborne explosive devices are generally referred to as shells and usually have a shorter range than missiles.
[src:blockade/aerial-warfare] In ordinary British-English usage predating guided weapons, a missile is "any thrown object", such as objects thrown at players by rowdy spectators at a sporting event.
[src:blockade/aerial-warfare] The advent of the unmanned aerial vehicle has dramatically revolutionised aerial warfare with multiple nations developing and/or purchasing UAV fleets.
[src:blockade/aerial-warfare] UAVs have quickly evolved from surveillance to combat roles.
[src:blockade/aerial-warfare] The growing capability of UAVs has thrown into question the survivability and capability of manned fighter jets.
[src:blockade/aerospace] The border between space and the atmosphere has been proposed as 100 kilometres (62.1 mi) above the ground according to the physical explanation that the air density is too low for a lifting body to generate meaningful lift force without exceeding orbital velocity.
[src:blockade/aerospace] This border has been called the Kármán line.
[src:blockade/aerospace] In most industrial countries, the aerospace industry is a co-operation of the public and private sectors.
[src:blockade/aerospace] Along with these public space programs, many companies produce technical tools and components such as spacecraft and satellites.
[src:blockade/aerospace] Some known companies involved in space programs include Boeing, Cobham, Airbus, SpaceX, Lockheed Martin, RTX Corporation, MDA and Northrop Grumman.
[src:blockade/aerospace] These companies are also involved in other areas of aerospace, such as the construction of aircraft.
[src:blockade/aerospace] Modern aerospace began with Engineer George Cayley in 1799.
[src:blockade/aerospace] Cayley proposed an aircraft with a "fixed wing and a horizontal and vertical tail," defining characteristics of the modern aeroplane.
[src:blockade/aerospace] The 19th century saw the creation of the Aeronautical Society of Great Britain (1866), the American Rocketry Society, and the Institute of Aeronautical Sciences, all of which made aeronautics a more serious scientific discipline.
[src:blockade/aerospace] Airmen like Otto Lilienthal, who introduced cambered airfoils in 1891, used gliders to analyze aerodynamic forces.
[src:blockade/aerospace] The Wright brothers were interested in Lilienthal's work and read several of his publications.
[src:blockade/aerospace] They also found inspiration in Octave Chanute, an airman and the author of *Progress in Flying Machines* (1894).
[src:blockade/aerospace] It was the preliminary work of Cayley, Lilienthal, Chanute, and other early aerospace engineers that brought about the first powered sustained flight at Kitty Hawk, North Carolina on December 17, 1903, by the Wright brothers.
[src:blockade/aerospace] War and science fiction inspired scientists and engineers like Konstantin Tsiolkovsky and Wernher von Braun to achieve flight beyond the atmosphere.
[src:blockade/aerospace] World War II inspired Wernher von Braun to create the V1 and V2 rockets.
[src:blockade/aerospace] The launch of Sputnik 1 in October 1957 started the Space Age, and on July 20, 1969 Apollo 11 achieved the first crewed Moon landing.
[src:blockade/aerospace] In April 1981, the Space Shuttle *Columbia* launched, the start of regular crewed access to orbital space.
[src:blockade/aerospace] A sustained human presence in orbital space started with "Mir" in 1986 and is continued by the "International Space Station".
[src:blockade/aerospace] Space commercialization and space tourism are more recent features of aerospace.
[src:blockade/aerospace] Aerospace manufacturing is a high-technology industry that produces "aircraft, guided missiles, space vehicles, aircraft engines, propulsion units, and related parts".
[src:blockade/aerospace] Most of the industry is geared toward governmental work.
[src:blockade/aerospace] For each original equipment manufacturer (OEM), the US government has assigned a Commercial and Government Entity (CAGE) code.
[src:blockade/aerospace] These codes help to identify each manufacturer, repair facilities, and other critical aftermarket vendors in the aerospace industry.
[src:blockade/aerospace] In the United States, the Department of Defense and the National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) are the two largest consumers of aerospace technology and products.
[src:blockade/aerospace] Others include the very large airline industry.
[src:blockade/aerospace] The aerospace industry employed 472,000 wage and salary workers in 2006.
[src:blockade/aerospace] Most of those jobs were in Washington state and in California, with Missouri, New York and Texas also being important.
[src:blockade/aerospace] The leading aerospace manufacturers in the U.S. are Boeing, United Technologies Corporation, SpaceX, Northrop Grumman and Lockheed Martin.
[src:blockade/aerospace] As talented American employees age and retire, these manufacturers face an expanding labor shortfall.
[src:blockade/aerospace] In order to supply the industrial sector with fresh workers, apprenticeship programs like the Aerospace Joint Apprenticeship Council (AJAC) collaborate with community colleges and aerospace firms in Washington state.
[src:blockade/aerospace] In the European Union, aerospace companies such as Airbus, Safran, Thales, Dassault Aviation, Leonardo and Saab AB account for a large share of the global aerospace industry and research effort, with the European Space Agency as one of the largest consumers of aerospace technology and products.
[src:blockade/aerospace] In India, Bangalore is a major center of the aerospace industry, where Hindustan Aeronautics Limited, the National Aerospace Laboratories and the Indian Space Research Organisation are headquartered.
[src:blockade/aerospace] The Indian Space Research Organisation (ISRO) launched India's first Moon orbiter, Chandrayaan-1, in October 2008.
[src:blockade/aerospace] In Russia, large aerospace companies like Oboronprom and the United Aircraft Building Corporation (encompassing Mikoyan, Sukhoi, Ilyushin, Tupolev, Yakovlev, and Irkut which includes Beriev) are among the major global players in this industry.
[src:blockade/aerospace] The historic Soviet Union was also the home of a major aerospace industry.
[src:blockade/aerospace] The United Kingdom attempted to maintain its own large aerospace industry, making its own airliners and warplanes, but it has largely turned to cooperative efforts with continental companies.
[src:blockade/aerospace] It also imports from countries such as the United States.
[src:blockade/aerospace] However, major companies such as BAE Systems supply fully assembled aircraft, aircraft components, sub-assemblies and sub-systems to other manufacturers, in Europe and other parts of the world.
[src:blockade/aerospace] Canada formerly manufactured some of its own designs for jet warplanes, etc.
[src:blockade/aerospace] (e.g. the CF-100 fighter), but it has come to rely on imports from the United States and Europe to fill these needs.
[src:blockade/aerospace] However Canada still manufactures some military aircraft.
[src:blockade/aerospace] Also notable is the late 1950s development of the Avro Canada CF-105 Arrow, a supersonic fighter-interceptor whose 1959 cancellation was controversial.
[src:blockade/aerospace] France has continued to make its own warplanes for its air force and navy, and Sweden continues to make its own warplanes for the Swedish Air Force—especially in support of its position as a neutral country.
[src:blockade/aerospace] (See Saab AB.) Other European countries either team up in making fighters (such as the Panavia Tornado and the Eurofighter Typhoon), or else to import them from the United States.
[src:blockade/aerospace] Pakistan has a developing aerospace engineering industry.
[src:blockade/aerospace] The National Engineering and Scientific Commission, Khan Research Laboratories and Pakistan Aeronautical Complex are among the premier organizations involved in research and development in this sector.
[src:blockade/aerospace] Pakistan has the capability of designing and manufacturing guided rockets, missiles and space vehicles.
[src:blockade/aerospace] The city of Kamra is home to the Pakistan Aeronautical Complex which contains several factories.
[src:blockade/aerospace] This facility is responsible for manufacturing the MFI-17, MFI-395, K-8 and JF-17 Thunder aircraft.
[src:blockade/aerospace] Pakistan also has the capability to design and manufacture both armed and unarmed unmanned aerial vehicles.
[src:blockade/aerospace] In the People's Republic of China, Beijing, Xi'an, Chengdu, Shanghai, Shenyang and Nanchang are major research and manufacture centers of the aerospace industry.
[src:blockade/aerospace] China has developed an extensive capability to design, test and produce military aircraft, missiles and space vehicles.
[src:blockade/aerospace] Despite the cancellation in 1983 of the experimental Shanghai Y-10, China is still developing its civil aerospace industry.
[src:blockade/aerospace] The aircraft parts industry was born out of the sale of second-hand or used aircraft parts from the aerospace manufacture sector.
[src:blockade/aerospace] Within the United States there is a specific process that parts brokers or resellers must follow.
[src:blockade/aerospace] This includes leveraging a certified repair station to overhaul and "tag" a part.
[src:blockade/aerospace] This certification guarantees that a part was repaired or overhauled to meet OEM specifications.
[src:blockade/aerospace] Once a part is overhauled its value is determined from the supply and demand of the aerospace market.
[src:blockade/aerospace] When an airline has an aircraft on the ground, the part that the airline requires to get the plane back into service becomes invaluable.
[src:blockade/aerospace] This can drive the market for specific parts.
[src:blockade/aerospace] There are several online marketplaces that assist with the commodity selling of aircraft parts.
[src:blockade/aerospace] In the aerospace and defense industry, much consolidation occurred at the end of the 20th century and in the early 21st century.
[src:blockade/aerospace] Between 1988 and 2011, more than 6,068 mergers and acquisitions with a total known value of US$678 billion were announced worldwide.
[src:blockade/aerospace] Functional safety relates to a part of the general safety of a system or a piece of equipment.
[src:blockade/aerospace] It implies that the system or equipment can be operated properly and without causing any danger, risk, damage or injury.
[src:blockade/aerospace] Functional safety is crucial in the aerospace industry, which allows no compromises or negligence.
[src:blockade/aerospace] In this respect, supervisory bodies, such as the European Aviation Safety Agency, regulate the aerospace market with strict certification standards.
[src:blockade/aerospace] This is meant to reach and ensure the highest possible level of safety.
[src:blockade/aerospace] The standards AS 9100 in America, EN 9100 on the European market or JISQ 9100 in Asia particularly address the aerospace and aviation industry.
[src:blockade/aerospace] These are standards applying to the functional safety of aerospace vehicles.
[src:blockade/aerospace] Some companies are therefore specialized in the certification, inspection, verification and testing of the vehicles and spare parts to ensure and attest compliance with the appropriate regulations.
[src:blockade/aerospace] Spinoffs refer to any technology that is a direct result of coding or products created by NASA and redesigned for an alternate purpose.
[src:blockade/aerospace] These technological advancements are one of the primary results of the aerospace industry, with $5.2 billion worth of revenue generated by spinoff technology, including computers and cellular devices.
[src:blockade/aerospace] These spinoffs have applications in a variety of different fields including medicine, transportation, energy, consumer goods, public safety and more.
[src:blockade/aerospace] NASA publishes an annual report called "Spinoffs", regarding many of the specific products and benefits to the aforementioned areas in an effort to highlight some of the ways funding is put to use.
[src:blockade/aerospace] For example, in the most recent edition of this publication, "Spinoffs 2015", endoscopes are featured as one of the medical derivations of aerospace achievement.
[src:blockade/aerospace] This device enables more precise and subsequently cost-effective neurosurgery by reducing complications through a minimally invasive procedure that abbreviates hospitalization.
[src:blockade/aerospace] "These NASA technologies are not only giving companies and entrepreneurs a competitive edge in their own industries, but are also helping to shape budding industries, such as commercial lunar landers," said Daniel Lockney.
[src:blockade/air-assault] Invariably the assaulting troops are highly dependent on aerial fire support provided by the attack helicopters, armed helicopters, and/or fixed-wing aircraft escorting them.
[src:blockade/air-assault] A concept called *mounted vertical maneuver* requires the ability to transport light, motorized, or medium-weight mechanized force by VTOL or super STOL aircraft.
[src:blockade/air-assault] Air assault should not be confused with *air attack*, *air strike*, or *air raid*, which all refer to attack using solely aircraft (for example bombing, strafing, etc.).
[src:blockade/air-assault] Moreover, air assault should not be confused with an airborne assault, which occurs when paratroopers, and their weapons and supplies, are dropped by parachute from transport aircraft, often as part of a strategic offensive operation.
[src:blockade/air-assault] Air assault and air mobility are related concepts.
[src:blockade/air-assault] However, air assault is distinctly a combat insertion rather than transportation to an area in the vicinity of combat.
[src:blockade/air-assault] Air assault units can vary in organization; using helicopters not only in transport but also as close air fire support, medical evacuation helicopters and resupply missions.
[src:blockade/air-assault] Airmobile artillery is often assigned to air assault deployments.
[src:blockade/air-assault] Units vary in size, but are typically company to brigade sized units.
[src:blockade/air-assault] Airmobile units are designed and trained for air insertion and vertical envelopment ("a maneuver in which troops, either air-dropped or air-landed, attack the rear and flanks of a force, in effect cutting off or encircling the force", air resupply, and if necessary air extraction.
[src:blockade/air-assault] One specific type of air assault unit is the US Army air cavalry.
[src:blockade/air-assault] It differs from regular air assault units only in fulfilling a traditional cavalry reconnaissance and short raids role.
[src:blockade/air-assault] Britain's 16 Air Assault Brigade was formed in 1999 following an amalgamation of elements of 5th Infantry Brigade (5 Airborne Brigade) and 24 Airmobile Brigade, bringing together the agility and reach of airborne forces with the potency of the attack helicopter.
[src:blockade/air-assault] Similarly, the US 101st Airborne Division was originally classed as airborne, then airmobile and now air assault.
[src:blockade/air-assault] Air mobility has been a key concept in offensive operations since the 1930s.
[src:blockade/air-assault] Initial approaches to air mobility focused on parachutists and the use of military gliders.
[src:blockade/air-assault] During World War II many assaults were done by military gliders.
[src:blockade/air-assault] The World War Two era German Fallschirmjäger, Brandenburgers, and the 22nd Air Landing Division glider borne paras laid the foundation for modern day air assault operations.
[src:blockade/air-assault] Army quickly adopted this concept of offensive operations initially utilizing wooden gliders before the development of helicopters.
[src:blockade/air-assault] Following the war, faster aircraft led to the abandonment of the flimsy wooden gliders with the then new helicopters taking their place.
[src:blockade/air-assault] In 1943 the Germans conducted the Gran Sasso raid which implemented many aspects of the air assault concept.
[src:blockade/air-assault] Another example was the German Brandenburgers' glider borne operation at Ypenburg during World War Two.
[src:blockade/air-assault] Geiger observed the atomic bomb tests at Bikini Atoll and instantly recognized that atomic bombs could render amphibious landings difficult because of the dense concentrations of troops, ships and material at beachheads.
[src:blockade/air-assault] During this time, The Commandant of the Marine Corps, Alexander Vandegrift, convened a special board known as the Hogaboom Board.
[src:blockade/air-assault] This board recommended that the USMC develop transport helicopters in order to allow a diffused attack on enemy shores.
[src:blockade/air-assault] It also recommended that the USMC form an experimental helicopter squadron.
[src:blockade/air-assault] HMX-1 was commissioned in 1947 with Sikorsky HO3S-1s.
[src:blockade/air-assault] In 1948 the Marine Corps Schools came out with *Amphibious Operations—Employment of Helicopters (Tentative)*, or *Phib-31*, which was the first US manual for helicopter airmobile operations.
[src:blockade/air-assault] The Marines used the term vertical envelopment instead of air mobility or air assault.
[src:blockade/air-assault] HMX-1 performed its first vertical envelopment from the deck of an aircraft carrier in an exercise in 1949.
[src:blockade/air-assault] American forces later used helicopters for support and transport to great effect during the Korean War showing that the helicopter could be a versatile and powerful military tool.
[src:blockade/air-assault] The first helicopter airlift and helicopter sling load mission was conducted on September 13, 1951, during the Korean War.
[src:blockade/air-assault] On November 5, 1956, the Royal Marines' 45 Commando performed the world's first combat helicopter insertion with air assault during an amphibious landing as part of Operation Musketeer, in Suez, Egypt.
[src:blockade/air-assault] 650 marines and 23 tons of equipment were flown in ten Westland Whirlwind Mark 2s of 845 Naval Air Squadron from the deck of HMS *Theseus*, and six each Whirlwinds and Bristol Sycamore HC.12s and HC.14s off HMS *Ocean*'s embarked Joint Experimental Helicopter Unit (JEHU) (Royal Air Force).
[src:blockade/air-assault] In 1956, the United States Marine Corps executed the first Division-strength exercise of vertical envelopment when the 1st Marine Division was helicopter-lifted from converted WWII jeep carriers to landing sites at Camp Pendleton, CA, U.S.
[src:blockade/air-assault] One of the ships utilized for this exercise was the USS *Thetis Bay*.
[src:blockade/air-assault] This exercise was the culmination of the Marines' developing strategy of vertical envelopment rather than amphibious assaults on heavily defended beaches.
[src:blockade/air-assault] The maneuvers were well-covered by the media of the time, including LIFE Magazine.
[src:blockade/air-assault] The Marine Corps subsequently adopted this method as standard operating procedure after proving that helicopters could be used to transport very large numbers of troops and large amounts of supplies in a timely fashion.
[src:blockade/air-assault] Operation Deep Water was a 1957 NATO naval exercise held in the Mediterranean Sea that involved the first units of the United States Marine Corps to participate in a helicopter-borne vertical envelopment operation during an overseas deployment.
[src:blockade/air-assault] Army's 1st Cavalry Division conducted the first large scale air assault operation in combat during the Battle of Ia Drang.
[src:blockade/air-assault] The use of armed helicopters coupled with helicopter transport during the Algerian War for the French Army to drop troops into enemy territory gave birth to the tactics of airmobile warfare that continues today.
[src:blockade/air-assault] The machines of the French Army Light Aviation carried out a considerable number of missions against Algerian insurgents between 1955, when the *Groupe d’Hélicoptères* No.2 (GH 2) was created, and 1962 when the French colonial rule in Algeria finally came to an end.
[src:blockade/air-assault] Acquiring these machines lay in the hands of the licensee Piasecki given France's urgent need to have them on account of the circumstances.
[src:blockade/air-assault] Usually, the H-21 could carry up to 18 troops, yet local operating (as well as climatic) conditions decreed that the French army examples could carry only up to around 12 troops each.
[src:blockade/air-assault] In two years, GH 2 received the vast majority of the H-21s acquired by ALAT, which consisted of five squadrons by the end of 1958.
[src:blockade/air-assault] A sixth squadron from the French naval air arm, the *Aéronautique navale*, had operated with GH 2 for little more than a year.
[src:blockade/air-assault] From 1955 to 1962, GH 2 took part in the major battles, which occurred near the frontier between Algeria and Tunisia, including the battle of Souk-Ahras in April 1958.
[src:blockade/air-assault] By the time the war in Algeria had ended, eight officers and 23 non-commissioned officers from ALAT had died in the course of their duties.
[src:blockade/air-assault] Army CH-21 helicopter transports arrived in South Vietnam on 11 December 1961.
[src:blockade/air-assault] Air assault operations using Army of the Republic of Vietnam (ARVN) troops began 12 days later in Operation Chopper.
[src:blockade/air-assault] These were very successful at first but the Viet Cong (VC) began developing counter helicopter techniques, and at the Battle of Ap Bac in January 1963, 13 of 15 helicopters were hit and four shot down.
[src:blockade/air-assault] The Army began adding machine guns and rockets to their smaller helicopters and developed the first purpose built gunship with the M-6E3 armament system.
[src:blockade/air-assault] Marine helicopter squadrons began four-month rotations through Vietnam as part of Operation SHUFLY on 15 April 1962.
[src:blockade/air-assault] Six days later, they performed the first helicopter assault using U.S.
[src:blockade/air-assault] After April 1963, as losses began to mount, U.S.
[src:blockade/air-assault] Army UH-1 Huey gunships escorted the Marine transports.
[src:blockade/air-assault] The VC again used effective counter landing techniques and in Operation Sure Wind 202 on 27 April 1964, 17 of 21 helicopters were hit and three shot down.
[src:blockade/air-assault] The 2nd Battalion 3rd Marines made a night helicopter assault in the Elephant Valley south of Da Nang on 13 August 1965 shortly after Marine ground troops arrived in country.
[src:blockade/air-assault] The transport helicopters were 24 UH-34s from HMM-361, HMM-261 and HMM-161 in relief, escorted by Marine and Army Hueys from VMO-2 and VMO-6 led by Maj Donald G.
[src:blockade/air-assault] Radcliff, US Army who was killed in action.
[src:blockade/air-assault] VC losses were 614 killed, Marine losses were 45 KIA and 203 WIA.
[src:blockade/air-assault] The need for a new type of unit became apparent to the Tactical Mobility Requirements Board (normally referred to as the Howze Board) of the U.S.
[src:blockade/air-assault] The Board met at a difficult time; the bulk of the military hierarchy were focused primarily on the Soviet threat to Western Europe, and perceived as requiring heavy, conventional units.
[src:blockade/air-assault] The creation of new, light airmobile units could only occur at the expense of heavier units.
[src:blockade/air-assault] At the same time, the incoming Kennedy administration was placing a much greater emphasis on the need to fight 'small wars', or counter-insurgencies, and was strongly supportive of officers such as General Howze who were embracing new technologies.
[src:blockade/air-assault] The Board concluded that a new form of unit would be required, and commissioned tests – but justified these at the time on the need to fight a conventional war in Europe.
[src:blockade/air-assault] Initially a new experimental unit was formed at Fort Benning, Georgia, the 11th Air Assault Division on 11 February 1963, combining light infantry with integral helicopter transport and air support.
[src:blockade/air-assault] Others have put more weight on the support of newly appointed senior Army commanders, including the new Chief of Staff General Wheeler, in driving through the changes.
[src:blockade/air-assault] Nonetheless, the 11th Air Assault Division assets were merged with the co-located 2nd Infantry Division and reflagged as the 1st Cavalry Division (Airmobile), continuing the tradition of the 1st Cavalry Division.
[src:blockade/air-assault] Within several months it was sent to Vietnam and the concept of air mobility became bound up with the challenges of that campaign, especially its varied terrain – the jungles, mountains, and rivers which complicated ground movement.
[src:blockade/air-assault] The first unit of the new division to see major combat was the 1st Battalion, 7th Cavalry Regiment, 1st Cavalry Division, led by Lieutenant Colonel Harold G.
[src:blockade/air-assault] The 7th Cavalry was the same regiment that Custer had commanded at the ill-fated Battle of the Little Bighorn.
[src:blockade/air-assault] On November 14, 1965, Moore led his troops in the first large unit engagement of the Vietnam War, which took place near the Chu Pong massif near the Vietnam-Cambodia border.
[src:blockade/air-assault] It is known today as the Battle of Ia Drang Valley, and is considered to be the first large scale helicopter air assault.
[src:blockade/air-assault] The Vietnam-era 1st Cavalry Division (Airmobile) was not an "air cavalry" division, per se, although it did contain air cavalry squadrons.
[src:blockade/air-assault] However, true "air assault" organizations are specialized light infantry (much like airborne troops), who are trained, organized, and equipped specifically to perform the complex, rapid, and dynamic tasks inherent in air assault vice simply being transported by aircraft.
[src:blockade/air-assault] Perhaps a rough comparison can be made between "motorized" and "mechanized" infantry.
[src:blockade/air-assault] Any light infantry unit can be transported by truck (viz., "motorized"), however, "mechanized" infantry are specifically trained, organized, and equipped to conduct operations in close-coordination with tanks.
[src:blockade/air-assault] The armed forces of Portugal, Rhodesia and South Africa widely conducted airmobile warfare operations in Southern Africa, during the Portuguese Colonial War (1961–1974), the Rhodesian Bush War (1964–1979) and the South African Border War (1966–1990).
[src:blockade/air-assault] The airmobile warfare was part of the counter-insurgency actions made by the forces of the three countries against guerrilla forces in Angola, Portuguese Guinea, Rhodesia, Mozambique and South-West Africa.
[src:blockade/air-assault] The airmobile warfare tactics used by Portugal, Rhodesia and South Africa had many similar characteristics.
[src:blockade/air-assault] The air forces of the three countries also used the same types of helicopters (mainly Alouette III and later, regarding Portugal and South Africa, SA 330 Puma), and there were military cooperation agreements and sharing of experience between the three powers, including the secret Alcora Exercise.
[src:blockade/air-assault] Portuguese, Rhodesian and South African airmobile tactics often involved air assaults done by small units of special forces or light infantry, transported in four or five Alouette III helicopters.
[src:blockade/air-assault] Assaults were often supported by an Alouette III armed with a side-mounted 20 mm MG 151 autocannon.
[src:blockade/air-assault] This helicopter was nicknamed *Helicanhão* (heli-cannon) by the Portuguese and *K-Car* by the Rhodesians.
[src:blockade/air-assault] Variants of the air mobile warfare tactics used in Africa included the Rhodesian Fireforce and the Portuguese heliborne-horseborne forces cooperation.
[src:blockade/air-assault] Meghna Heli Bridge was an aerial operation of Indian and Bangladeshi allied forces during the Bangladesh Liberation War in 1971.
[src:blockade/air-assault] It took place on 9 December, when the Indian Air Force airlifted the Mukti Bahini and the IV Corps of the Indian Army from Brahmanbaria to Raipura in Narsingdi over the River Meghna, bypassing the destroyed Meghna Bridge and Pakistani defences in Ashuganj.
[src:blockade/air-assault] In the United States Army, the air assault mission is the primary role of the 101st Airborne Division (Air Assault).
[src:blockade/air-assault] This unit is a division-sized helicopter-borne fighting force.
[src:blockade/air-assault] 101st Airborne Division soldiers attend the Sabalauski Air Assault School.
[src:blockade/air-assault] Graduates are qualified to insert and extract using fast rope and rappel means from a hover in addition to the ordinary walk on and off from an airlanded helicopter.
[src:blockade/air-assault] Marine Corps divisions are capable of, and routinely train for and perform, air assault operations.
[src:blockade/air-assault] Forward-deployed Marine Corps infantry battalions/regiments (reinforced, organized, and designated as Battalion Landing Teams/Regimental Combat Teams, or BLTs and RCTs, respectively), form the Ground Combat Element (GCE) of a Marine Expeditionary Unit (MEU), or Marine Expeditionary Brigade (MEB).
[src:blockade/air-assault] These MEUs and MEBs are capable of embarking aboard amphibious warships and include air assault as one of several means of conducting amphibious landing operations, supported by embarked Marine Corps tilt-rotor, helicopter, and STOVL fixed-wing strike aircraft.
[src:blockade/air-assault] The 10th Mountain Division Light Infantry has a limited capability to perform air assault operations.
[src:blockade/air-assault] On September 19, 1994, the 1st Brigade of the 10th Mountain Division conducted the Army's first air assault from an aircraft carrier, the USS *Dwight D.
[src:blockade/air-assault] Eisenhower*, as part of Operation Uphold Democracy.
[src:blockade/air-assault] This force consisted of 54 helicopters and almost 2,000 soldiers.
[src:blockade/air-assault] The 16th Air Assault Brigade of the British Army is the UK's main air assault body.
[src:blockade/air-assault] It comprises units of paratroopers from the Parachute Regiment and light infantry units trained in helicopter insertion, as well as light tanks and artillery.
[src:blockade/air-assault] Britain's 3 Commando Brigade Royal Marines are also highly experienced in air assault, both for boarding ships and in land attacks, see article above.
[src:blockade/air-assault] The Battle of Antonov Airport was an operation during the opening days of the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine where the Russian Airborne Forces (VDV) attempted an air assault in order to capture Hostomel Airport, in order to use the airport to airlift troops and heavy equipment directly into Kyiv.
[src:blockade/air-assault] The VDV was initially able to capture the airport, but without artillery or armored support they were not able to handle a counter-attack started by local Ukrainian forces.
[src:blockade/air-assault] The airport was captured only on the second day by a second air assault combined with an armored push from ground troops.
[src:blockade/air-assault] A simultaneous air assault was attempted at Vasylkiv, where VDV paratroopers attempted to seize the Vasylkiv Air Base but the attack was repelled.
[src:blockade/air-combat-manoeuvring] Military aviation originated in World War I when aircraft were initially used to spot enemy troop concentrations, field gun positions, and movements.
[src:blockade/air-combat-manoeuvring] Early aerial combat consisted of aviators shooting at one another with hand-held weapons.
[src:blockade/air-combat-manoeuvring] The first recorded aircraft to be shot down by another aircraft, which occurred on October 5, 1914, was a German Aviatik B.I.
[src:blockade/air-combat-manoeuvring] The pilot, Feldwebel Wilhelm Schlichting, was shot with a carbine wielded by observer Louis Quenault, who was riding in a French Voisin III piloted by Sergeant Joseph Frantz.
[src:blockade/air-combat-manoeuvring] The need to stop reconnaissance that was being conducted by enemy aircraft rapidly led to the development of fighter planes, a class of aircraft designed specifically to destroy other aircraft.
[src:blockade/air-combat-manoeuvring] Fixed, forward-firing guns were found to be the most effective armament for a majority of World War I era fighter planes, but it was nearly impossible to fire them through the spinning propeller of one's own aircraft without destroying one's own plane.
[src:blockade/air-combat-manoeuvring] Roland Garros, working with Morane Saulnier Aéroplanes, was the first to solve this problem by attaching steel deflector wedges to the propeller.
[src:blockade/air-combat-manoeuvring] He achieved three kills but was shot down by ground fire and landed behind German lines.
[src:blockade/air-combat-manoeuvring] Anthony Fokker inspected the plane's wreckage and learned to improve the design by connecting the firing mechanism of the gun to the timing of the engine, thus allowing the gun to fire through the propeller without making contact with the propeller.
[src:blockade/air-combat-manoeuvring] As technology rapidly advanced, new and young aviators began defining the realm of air-to-air combat, such as Max Immelmann, Oswald Boelcke, and Lanoe Hawker.
[src:blockade/air-combat-manoeuvring] One of the greatest of these "ace pilots" of World War I, Manfred von Richthofen (the Red Baron), wrote in his book *The Red Fighter Pilot*, "The great thing in air fighting is that the decisive factor does not lie in trick flying but solely in the personal ability and energy of the aviator.
[src:blockade/air-combat-manoeuvring] Pilots soon learned to achieve a firing position (while avoiding the threat of enemy guns) by manoeuvring themselves behind an enemy aircraft; this is known as getting onto an aircraft's "six o'clock" or onto their "tail", plus a wide variety of other terms, usually coined by air crew.
[src:blockade/air-combat-manoeuvring] This type of combat became known as dogfighting.
[src:blockade/air-combat-manoeuvring] Oswald Boelcke, a German fighter ace during World War I, was the first to publish the basic rules for aerial combat manoeuvring in 1916, known as the *Dicta Boelcke*.
[src:blockade/air-combat-manoeuvring] He advised pilots to attack from the direction of the sun (toward which the defending pilot could not see), or to fly at a higher altitude than the opponent.
[src:blockade/air-combat-manoeuvring] Most of these rules are still as valuable today as they were a century ago.
[src:blockade/air-combat-manoeuvring] Today's air combat is much more complicated than that of older times, as air-to-air missiles, radar, and automatic cannons capable of high rates of fire are used on nearly all modern fighter aircraft.
[src:blockade/air-combat-manoeuvring] However, close-range fighting with infrared guided missiles and aircraft cannons still obeys the same general rules laid down in the skies over Europe in the early 20th century.
[src:blockade/air-combat-manoeuvring] The master rule is still the same: get on the opponent's rear without allowing them to do the same.
[src:blockade/air-combat-manoeuvring] Close-range combat tactics vary considerably according to the type of aircraft being used and the number of aircraft involved.
[src:blockade/air-combat-manoeuvring] There are five things a pilot must remain aware of when contemplating aerial engagement; of these, seeing and keeping sight of one's opponent are the most important.
[src:blockade/air-combat-manoeuvring] In Southeast Asia, over 85 percent of all kills are attributed to the attacker spotting and shooting the defender without ever being seen.
[src:blockade/air-combat-manoeuvring] Structural limitations of the attacking and defending fighters must be taken into account, such as thrust-to-weight ratio, wing loading, and the "corner speed" (the maximum or minimum speed at which the aircraft can attain the best turning performance).
[src:blockade/air-combat-manoeuvring] Variable limitations must also be considered, such as turn radius, turn rate and the specific energy of the aircraft.
[src:blockade/air-combat-manoeuvring] Position of aircraft must quickly be assessed, including direction, angle off tail (the angle between flight paths), and closing speed.
[src:blockade/air-combat-manoeuvring] Also, the pilot must be aware of his wingman's position and maintain good communication.
[src:blockade/air-combat-manoeuvring] A pilot in combat attempts to conserve his aircraft's energy through carefully timed and executed manoeuvres.
[src:blockade/air-combat-manoeuvring] By using such manoeuvres, a pilot will often make trade offs between the fighter's potential energy (altitude) and kinetic energy (airspeed), to maintain the energy-to-weight ratio of the aircraft, or the "specific energy".
[src:blockade/air-combat-manoeuvring] A manoeuvre such as the "low yo-yo" trades altitude for airspeed to close on an enemy and to decrease turn radius.
[src:blockade/air-combat-manoeuvring] The opposite manoeuvre, a "high yo-yo", trades speed for height, literally storing energy in "the altitude bank", which allows a fast moving attacker to slow his closing speed.
[src:blockade/air-combat-manoeuvring] An attacker is confronted with three possible ways to pursue an enemy, all of which are vital during chase.
[src:blockade/air-combat-manoeuvring] "Lag pursuit" happens in a turn when the nose of the attacker's aircraft points behind an enemy's tail.
[src:blockade/air-combat-manoeuvring] Lag pursuit allows an attacker to increase or maintain range without overshooting.
[src:blockade/air-combat-manoeuvring] "Lead pursuit" in a turn occurs when the nose of the attacking aircraft points ahead of the enemy.
[src:blockade/air-combat-manoeuvring] Lead pursuit is used to decrease the distance between aircraft, and during gun attacks when the cannons must be aimed, not at where the defender is, but where he will be when the bullets get there.
[src:blockade/air-combat-manoeuvring] "Pure pursuit" happens when the nose of the attacker points directly at the defender.
[src:blockade/air-combat-manoeuvring] Pure pursuit is when most missiles will be fired, and is the hardest position to maintain.
[src:blockade/air-combat-manoeuvring] The turning battle of a dogfight can be executed in an infinite number of geometric planes.
[src:blockade/air-combat-manoeuvring] Pilots are encouraged to keep their manoeuvres out of the strictly vertical and horizontal planes, but to instead use the limitless number of oblique planes, which is much harder for an adversary to track.
[src:blockade/air-combat-manoeuvring] This infinite number of planes around a fixed point about which the aircraft turns is termed the "post and bubble".
[src:blockade/air-combat-manoeuvring] A fighter that can maintain position between an aircraft and its imaginary post cannot be attacked by that aircraft.
[src:blockade/air-combat-manoeuvring] The imaginary bubble, however, is misshapen by gravity, causing turns to be much tighter and slower at the top, and wider and faster at the bottom, and is sometimes referred to as a "tactical egg".
[src:blockade/air-combat-manoeuvring] The manoeuvres employed by the attacker can also be used by the defender to evade, or gain a tactical advantage over his opponent.
[src:blockade/air-combat-manoeuvring] Other components may also be employed to manoeuvre the aircraft, such as yaw, drag, lift, and thrust vectors.
[src:blockade/air-combat-manoeuvring] A key factor in all battles is that of "nose-tail separation".
[src:blockade/air-combat-manoeuvring] While getting close enough to fire a weapon, an attacker must keep his aircraft's nose far enough away from the tail of the defender to be able to get a good aim, and to prevent an overshoot.
[src:blockade/air-combat-manoeuvring] The defender, likewise, will use every manoeuvre available to encourage an overshoot, trying to change his own role to that of attacker.
[src:blockade/air-force] An **air force** in the broadest sense is the national military branch that primarily conducts aerial warfare.
[src:blockade/air-force] More specifically, it is the branch of a nation's armed services that is responsible for aerial warfare as distinct from an army aviation or naval aviation units.
[src:blockade/air-force] Typically, air forces are responsible for gaining control of the air, carrying out strategic and tactical bombing missions, and providing support to land and naval forces often in the form of aerial reconnaissance and close air support.
[src:blockade/air-force] The term air force may also refer to a tactical air force or numbered air force, which is an operational formation either within a national air force or comprising several air components from allied nations.
[src:blockade/air-force] Air forces typically consist of a combination of fighters, bombers, helicopters, transport planes and other aircraft.
[src:blockade/air-force] Many air forces may command and control other air defence forces assets such as anti-aircraft artillery, surface-to-air missiles, or anti-ballistic missile warning networks and defensive systems.
[src:blockade/air-force] Some air forces are also responsible for operations of the military space and intercontinental ballistic missiles (ICBM).
[src:blockade/air-force] Some nations, principally countries who modelled their militaries along Soviet lines, have or had an air defence force which is organizationally separate from their air force.
[src:blockade/air-force] Peacetime/non-wartime activities of air forces may include air policing and air-sea rescue.
[src:blockade/air-force] Air forces are not just composed of pilots, but also rely on a significant amount of support from other personnel to operate.
[src:blockade/air-force] Logistics, security, intelligence, special operations, cyber space support, maintenance, weapons loaders, and many other specialties are required by all air forces.
[src:blockade/air-force] The first aviation force in the world was the Aviation Military of the French Army formed in 1910, which eventually became l'Armée de l'Air.
[src:blockade/air-force] In 1911, during the Italo-Turkish War, Italy employed aircraft for the first time ever in the world for reconnaissance and bombing missions against Turkish positions on Libyan Territory.
[src:blockade/air-force] This was the first war in history that featured air attacks by airplanes and dirigible airships.
[src:blockade/air-force] During World War I France, Germany, Italy, the British Empire and the Ottoman Empire all possessed significant forces of bombers and fighters.
[src:blockade/air-force] Aviation in World War I also saw the appearance of senior commanders who directed aerial warfare and numerous flying aces.
[src:blockade/air-force] An independent air force is one which is a separate branch of a nation's armed forces and is, at least nominally, treated as a military service on par with that of older services like navies or armies.
[src:blockade/air-force] The British Royal Air Force was the first independent air force in the world.
[src:blockade/air-force] The RAF was founded on 1 April 1918 by amalgamation the British Army's Royal Flying Corps and the Royal Naval Air Service.
[src:blockade/air-force] At its inception, the RAF comprised over 20,000 aircraft.
[src:blockade/air-force] It was commanded by a Chief of the Air Staff with the rank of major-general and was governed by its own government ministry (the Air Ministry).
[src:blockade/air-force] Arguably, the Finnish Air Force was the first independent air force in the world, formed on 6 March 1918, when the Swedish count, Eric von Rosen gave Finland the second aircraft, a Thulin Typ D.
[src:blockade/air-force] Some considered that the Finnish Air Force did not officially exist during the Finnish Civil War (27 January – 15 May 1918), and the Red Guards had its own air force.
[src:blockade/air-force] Over the following decades, most countries with substantial military capability established independent air forces.
[src:blockade/air-force] The Canadian Air Force was formed at the end of World War I and was abolished and reorganized several times between 1918 and 1924.
[src:blockade/air-force] It became the permanent Royal Canadian Air Force when it received the *Royal* title by royal proclamation on 1 April 1924.
[src:blockade/air-force] It did not however become independent of the Canadian Army until 1938, when its head was also designated as Chief of the Air Staff.
[src:blockade/air-force] Similarly, the Royal New Zealand Air Force was established in 1923 as the New Zealand Permanent Air Force, but did not become independent of the New Zealand Army until 1937.
[src:blockade/air-force] The Royal Indian Air Force was also formed on 8 October 1932.
[src:blockade/air-force] Other British-influenced countries also established independent air forces.
[src:blockade/air-force] For example, the Royal Egyptian Air Force was created in 1937, when Egyptian military aviation was separated from Army command.
[src:blockade/air-force] The Afghan Air Force was established on 22 August 1924, with support from the Soviet Union and Great Britain, but a civil war destroyed most of the planes and it was not reestablished until 1937, when King Mohammed Nadir Shah took power.
[src:blockade/air-force] Both the United States Air Force and the Philippine Air Force were formed as a separate branches of their respective armed forces in 1947, as did the Argentine Air Force in 1945.
[src:blockade/air-force] The Israeli Air Force came into being with the State of Israel on 18 May 1948, but evolved from the pre-existing Sherut Avir (Air Service) of the Haganah paramilitary.
[src:blockade/air-force] The Japan Air Self-Defense Force was not established until 1954; in World War II Japanese military aviation had been carried out by the Army and Navy.
[src:blockade/air-force] Unlike all these countries, the Mexican Air Force remains an integral part of the Mexican Army.
[src:blockade/air-force] Germany was the first country to organize regular air attacks on enemy infrastructure with the Luftstreitkräfte.
[src:blockade/air-force] In World War I, its zeppelins (airships) dropped bombs on British cities.
[src:blockade/air-force] British warplanes mostly spotted for artillery and fought German planes, British airships were less advanced than the zeppelins and mostly hunted for German U-boats (submarines).
[src:blockade/air-force] Fixed-wing aircraft at the time were quite primitive, being able to achieve velocities comparable to that of modern automobiles and mounting minimal weaponry and equipment.
[src:blockade/air-force] Aerial services were still largely a new venture, and relatively unreliable machines and limited training resulted in stupendously low life expectancies for early military aviators.
[src:blockade/air-force] By the time World War II began, planes had become much safer, faster, and more reliable.
[src:blockade/air-force] They were adopted as standard for bombing raids and taking out other aircraft because they were much faster than airships.
[src:blockade/air-force] The world's largest military Air Force by the start of the Second World War in 1939 was the Soviet Red Air Force, and although much depleted, it would stage the largest air operations of WWII over the four years of combat with the German Luftwaffe.
[src:blockade/air-force] Arguably the war's most important air operation, known as the Battle of Britain, took place during 1940 over Britain and the English Channel between Britain's Royal Air Force and Germany's Luftwaffe over a period of several months.
[src:blockade/air-force] In the end Britain emerged victorious, and this caused Adolf Hitler to give up his plan to invade Britain.
[src:blockade/air-force] Other prominent air force operations during the Second World War include the Allied bombing of Germany during 1942–1944, and the Red Air Force operations in support of strategic ground offensives on the Eastern Front.
[src:blockade/air-force] The aerial warfare in Pacific Ocean theatre was of a comparable strategic significance to the Battle of Britain but was largely conducted by the US and Japanese naval aviation services and not by air forces.
[src:blockade/air-force] The air force's role of strategic bombing against enemy infrastructure was developed during the 1930s by the Japanese in China and by the Germans during the Spanish Civil War.
[src:blockade/air-force] This role for the bomber was perfected during World War II, during Allied "Thousand Bomber Raid" operations.
[src:blockade/air-force] The need to intercept these bombers, both during the day and at night, accelerated fighter aircraft developments.
[src:blockade/air-force] The war ended when United States Army Air Forces Boeing B-29 Superfortress bombers dropped atomic bombs on Hiroshima and Nagasaki in Japan in August 1945.
[src:blockade/air-force] The United States Air Force became an independent service in 1947.
[src:blockade/air-force] As the Cold War began, both the USAF and the Soviet Air Force built up their nuclear-capable strategic bomber forces.
[src:blockade/air-force] Several technological advances were widely introduced during this time: the jet engine; the missile; the helicopter; and inflight refueling.
[src:blockade/air-force] In 1954 the Japan Air Self-Defense Force was founded as a separate service.
[src:blockade/air-force] Previously Japan had delivered its service aviation from within its Army and Navy.
[src:blockade/air-force] During the 1960s, Canada merged the Royal Canadian Air Force with the army and the navy to form the unified Canadian Forces, with air assets divided between several commands and a green uniform for everyone.
[src:blockade/air-force] This proved very unpopular, and in 1975 Canadian aviation units were reorganized under a single organization (Air Command) with a single commander.
[src:blockade/air-force] In 2011 the Canadian Forces Air Command reverted to its pre-1960s name, the Royal Canadian Air Force.
[src:blockade/air-force] The organizational structures of air forces vary between nations: some air forces (such as the United States Air Force, the Royal Air Force) are divided into commands, groups and squadrons; others (such as the Soviet Air Force) have an Army-style organizational structure.
[src:blockade/air-force] The modern Royal Canadian Air Force uses Air Division as the formation between wings and the entire air command.
[src:blockade/air-force] Like the RAF, Canadian wings consist of squadrons.
[src:blockade/air-force] In the case of China the Air Force headquarters consists of four departments: Command, Political, Logistic, and Equipment, which mirrors the four general departments of the People's Liberation Army.
[src:blockade/air-force] Below the headquarters, Military Region Air Forces (MRAF) direct divisions (Fighter, Attack, Bomber), which in turn direct regiments and squadrons.
[src:blockade/air-force] Air assault and Airborne infantry in air forces are used primarily for ground-based defense of air bases and other air force facilities.
[src:blockade/air-force] They also have a number of other specialist roles, including Chemical, Biological, Radiological and Nuclear (CBRN) defense, offensive operations in defense of air force assets, and training other air force personnel in basic ground defense tactics.
[src:blockade/air-force] Some air forces also include special forces which are used in a variety of roles including combat search and rescue, special reconnaissance, direct action, counterinsurgency, intelligence operations, and serving as joint terminal attack controllers attached to ground and special operations forces.
[src:blockade/air-power] Airpower can be considered a function of air supremacy and numbers.
[src:blockade/air-power] Roughly speaking, a combatant side that has 100% or near 100% control of the skies has air supremacy; an advantage of some 70–90% would indicate air superiority.
[src:blockade/air-power] A 50/50 split is air parity; lower than this, one side may be said to be air denied or air incapable.
[src:blockade/air-power] Because aeroplanes generally take off from designed airfields on missions typically involving some hours of cruising, the precise state of air superiority is fluid and less defined vis-a-vis land or sea warfare.
[src:blockade/air-power] For example, a contested airspace directly above a battlespace bristling with anti-aircraft weapons may be denied to the air forces of both sides.
[src:blockade/air-power] Significant contributors to theorizing about air power have been Giulio Douhet, Billy Mitchell, John Boyd and John A.
[src:blockade/air-power] At the start of World War I, opinions differed on the national air forces and the value of airships.
[src:blockade/air-power] Some early strategists/visionaries after World War I imagined that airpower alone would suffice to bring nations to their knees.
[src:blockade/air-power] The Bombing of Guernica was an early trial that revealed both capabilities and limitations.
[src:blockade/air-power] But yet another maxim, "no war was ever won solely by airpower" was challenged by the NATO victory in Kosovo.
[src:blockade/air-power] Airpower has been used to conduct lightning strategic strikes, to complement land offensives, to instill fear and lower morale similarly to a fleet in being, and to create broad-based destruction behind enemy lines.
[src:blockade/air-power] With airpower, supplies can be transported by cargo planes, providing a decisive edge in mobility.
[src:blockade/air-power] Airpower also relates to space power, although militarization of space remains regulated by international treaty.
[src:blockade/air-power] Developed nations have enjoyed a consistent advantage in airpower since the beginning of mechanized flight.
[src:blockade/air-power] Airpower has been wielded mostly decisively in the last hundred years by Nazi Germany, the United Kingdom, the United States, the Soviet Union, Japan, Italy, and France, with many client nations using aircraft developed by one or more of these nations.
[src:blockade/air-power] A mass technological base is considered necessary for the development of airpower.
[src:blockade/air-power] As early as 1921, air power doctrines were being actively debated in British India, with key arguments around flexibility, psychological impact, and deterrence being articulated by military theorists.
[src:blockade/air-power] These ideas, though born in the colonial era, later influenced independent air forces like the IAF.
[src:blockade/air-power] A retrospective analysis of these early insights and their enduring relevance has been published.
[src:blockade/blockade] A **blockade** is the use of military force to prevent food, supplies, weapons, or communications, and sometimes people, entering or leaving a country or region.
[src:blockade/blockade] Unlike sanctions or an embargo, which are legal barriers to trade, a blockade is physical.
[src:blockade/blockade] Blockades are distinct from sieges in that a blockade is usually directed at an entire country or region, rather than a fortress or city, and the objective of a blockade is not necessarily to conquer the area.
[src:blockade/blockade] A blockading power can seek to cut off all maritime transport from and to the blockaded country, although stopping all land transport to and from an area may also be considered a blockade.
[src:blockade/blockade] Blockades restrict the trading rights of neutral parties, who must submit for inspection for contraband, which the blockading power may define narrowly or broadly, sometimes including food and medicine.
[src:blockade/blockade] In the 20th century, air power has also been used to enhance the effectiveness of blockades by halting air traffic within the blockaded airspace.
[src:blockade/blockade] Close patrol of hostile ports, in order to prevent naval forces from putting to sea, is also referred to as a blockade.
[src:blockade/blockade] When coastal cities or fortresses were besieged from the landward side, the besiegers would often blockade the seaward side as well.
[src:blockade/blockade] Modern blockades have included cutting off electronic communications by jamming radio signals and severing undersea cables.
[src:blockade/blockade] Blockades often result in the starvation of the civilian population, notably during the blockade of Germany during World War I and the blockade of Biafra during the Nigerian Civil War.
[src:blockade/blockade] Although primitive naval blockades have been in use for millennia, early attempts were limited by the time ships were able to stay at sea uninterruptedly.
[src:blockade/blockade] The first successful attempts at establishing a full naval blockade were made by the British Royal Navy during the Seven Years' War (1754–1763) against France.
[src:blockade/blockade] Following the 1759 British naval victory at Quiberon Bay, which ended any immediate threat of a major invasion of Britain, the British Royal Navy established a close blockade on the French coast.
[src:blockade/blockade] This starved French ports of commerce, weakening France's economy.
[src:blockade/blockade] Admiral Edward Hawke took command of the blockading fleet off Brest and extended the blockade to cover the entire French Atlantic coast from Dunkirk to Bordeaux, and to Marseille on France's Mediterranean coast.
[src:blockade/blockade] During the North American operations of the Seven Years' War, the British Royal Navy blockaded the French on the other side of the Atlantic, specifically impeding access and supply to the colonies of New France on the St.
[src:blockade/blockade] Blockades contributed to the French loss of Canada in 1763.
[src:blockade/blockade] The strategic importance of blockade became increasingly apparent during the French Revolutionary Wars of 1792 to 1802 and in the Napoleonic Wars of 1803 to 1815, when the Royal Navy successfully blockaded France, leading to major economic disruptions.
[src:blockade/blockade] The Union blockade of southern ports was a major factor in the American Civil War of 1861 to 1865.
[src:blockade/blockade] During World War I (1914–1918), the Allies blockaded the Central Powers, depriving them of food-supplies and strategic materials.
[src:blockade/blockade] Germany's attempted U-boat blockade of Britain caused some shortages, but ultimately failed.
[src:blockade/blockade] A similar outcome followed in World War II (1939–1945).
[src:blockade/blockade] Naval strategic thinkers, such as Sir Julian Corbett (1854–1922) and Alfred Thayer Mahan (1840–1914), wrote that naval conflicts were won primarily by decisive battles, but also by blockade.
[src:blockade/blockade] A *close* blockade entails placing warships within sight of the blockaded coast or port, to ensure the immediate interception of any ship entering or leaving.
[src:blockade/blockade] It is both the most effective and the most difficult form of blockade to implement.
[src:blockade/blockade] Difficulties arise because the blockading ships must remain continuously at sea, exposed to storms and hardship, usually far from any support, and vulnerable to sudden attack from the blockaded side, whose ships may stay safe in harbor until they choose to come out.
[src:blockade/blockade] In a *distant* blockade, the blockaders stay well away from the blockaded coast and try to intercept any ships going in or out.
[src:blockade/blockade] This may require more ships on station, but they can usually operate closer to their bases, and are at much less risk from enemy raids.
[src:blockade/blockade] This was almost impossible prior to the 16th century due to the nature of the ships used.
[src:blockade/blockade] A *loose* blockade is a close blockade where the blockading ships are withdrawn out of sight from the coast, behind the horizon, but no farther.
[src:blockade/blockade] The object of loose blockade is to lure the enemy into venturing out but to stay close enough to strike.
[src:blockade/blockade] British admiral Horatio Nelson applied a loose blockade at Cádiz in 1805.
[src:blockade/blockade] The Franco-Spanish fleet under Pierre-Charles Villeneuve then came out, resulting in the Battle of Trafalgar.
[src:blockade/blockade] Until 1827, blockades, as part of economic warfare, were always a part of a war.
[src:blockade/blockade] This changed when France, Russia and Britain came to the aid of the Greek rebels against Turkey.
[src:blockade/blockade] They blockaded the Turkish-occupied coast, which led to the battle of Navarino.
[src:blockade/blockade] War was never declared, so it is considered the first *pacific* – i.e., peaceful – blockade.
[src:blockade/blockade] The first truly pacific blockade, involving no shooting at all, was the British blockade of the Republic of New Granada in 1837, established to compel New Granada to release an imprisoned British consul.
[src:blockade/blockade] Since 1945, the United Nations Security Council determines the legal status of blockades.
[src:blockade/blockade] By article 42 of the UN Charter, the council can also apply blockades.
[src:blockade/blockade] The UN Charter allows for the right of self-defense but requires that this must be immediately reported to the Security Council to ensure the maintenance of international peace.
[src:blockade/blockade] According to the not ratified document San Remo Manual on International Law Applicable to Armed Conflicts at Sea, June 1994, a blockade is a legal method of warfare at sea, but is governed by rules.
[src:blockade/blockade] The manual describes what can never be contraband.
[src:blockade/blockade] The blockading nation is free to select anything else as contraband in a list, which it must publish.
[src:blockade/blockade] The blockading nation typically establishes a blockaded area of water, and any ship can be inspected as soon as it is established that it is attempting to break the blockade.
[src:blockade/blockade] This inspection can occur inside the blockaded area or in international waters, but never inside the territorial waters of a neutral nation.
[src:blockade/blockade] A neutral ship must obey a request to stop for inspection from the blockading nation.
[src:blockade/blockade] If the situation so demands, the blockading nation can request that the ship divert to a known place or harbour for inspection.
[src:blockade/blockade] If the ship does not stop, then the ship is subject to capture.
[src:blockade/blockade] If people aboard the ship resist capture, they can be lawfully attacked.
[src:blockade/blockade] According to modern international law, blockades are an act of war.
[src:blockade/blockade] A blockade is therefore only legal if applied in self-defense, and not as part of a war of aggression.
[src:blockade/blockade] Blockades are illegal when used as to starve or to collectively punish a civilian population.
[src:blockade/blockade] Such a blockade is a war crime and potentially a crime against humanity.
[src:blockade/blockade] Blockade running is the practice of delivering cargo, food, for example, to a blockaded area.
[src:blockade/blockade] It has mainly been done by ships called blockade runners to ports under naval blockade.
[src:blockade/blockade] Blockade runners were typically the fastest ships available and often lightly armed and armored.
[src:blockade/blockade] It is now also done by aircraft, forming airbridges, such as over the Berlin Blockade after World War II.
